or exile for the sole crime of their existing, was the set to which he too belonged. His dark youthful broodings, the romantic — and let me add, somewhat artificial — passion for his mother's land, could not, I am sure, exclude real affection for the country where he had been born and bred.

After having tumbled silently into Finland, we lived for a time in Helsingfors. Then our ways parted. My mother acting on the suggestion of an old friend took me to Paris, where I continued my education.